{"id":"1606.02243","submitter":"Stefan Kettemann","authors":"Stefan Kettemann","title":"Exponential Orthogonality Catastrophe at the Anderson Metal-Insulator\n  Transition","comments":"4 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 117, 146602 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.117.146602","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the orthogonality catastrophe at the Anderson Metal-Insulator\ntransition (AMIT). The typical overlap $F$ between the ground state of a Fermi\nliquid and the one of the same system with an added potential impurity is found\nto decay at the AMIT exponentially with system size $L$ as $F \\sim \\exp (-\n\\langle I_A\\rangle /2)= \\exp(-c L^{\\eta})$, where $I_A$ is the so called\nAnderson integral, $\\eta $ is the power of multifractal intensity correlations\nand $\\langle ... \\rangle$ denotes the ensemble average. Thus, strong disorder\ntypically increases the sensitivity of a system to an additional impurity\nexponentially. We recover on the metallic side of the transition Anderson's\nresult that fidelity $F$ decays with a power law $F \\sim L^{-q (E_F)}$ with\nsystem size $L$. This power increases as Fermi energy $E_F$ approaches mobility\nedge $E_M$ as $q (E_F) \\sim (\\frac{E_F-E_M}{E_M})^{-\\nu \\eta},$ where $\\nu$ is\nthe critical exponent of correlation length $\\xi_c$. On the insulating side of\nthe transition $F$ is constant for system sizes exceeding localization length\n$\\xi$. While these results are obtained from the mean value of $I_A,$ giving\nthe typical fidelity $F$, we find that $I_A$ is widely, log normally,\ndistributed with a width diverging at the AMIT. As a consequence, the mean\nvalue of fidelity $F$ converges to one at the AMIT, in strong contrast to its\ntypical value which converges to zero exponentially fast with system size $L$.\nThis counterintuitive behavior is explained as a manifestation of\nmultifractality at the AMIT.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 7 Jun 2016 18:21:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-03"}
